        "description": [
          "Page 2: The high ability treatment called the \u00c3\u00a2\u00c2\u0080\u00c2\u009cvanguard' program consisted, with some variation among schools, of separate instruction in reading, language, mathe\u00c3\u0082\u00c2\u00ad matics, and science while students were mixed in phys\u00c3\u0082\u00c2\u00ad ical education, home room, recess, music, and art. In addition, high ability students took Spanish, seemed to be assigned better teachers, and were given optional supplementary materials while the basic curriculum re\u00c3\u0082\u00c2\u00ad mained the same for both groups. Occasionally, com\u00c3\u0082\u00c2\u00ad pensatory treat ment was given to regular students, e.g., one school chose to offer Latin to them. This model can be described as complete ability grouping (Findley & Bryan, 1975).",
          "Page 1: bility grouping is the method of assigning students to separate classrooms so that children of a par\u00c3\u0082\u00c2\u00ad ticular age and grade who function similarly in learning achievement and capability are placed together for instruction"
